#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:37
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Intro\n"
"-----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:42
msgid ""
"If you've used mandrake, and seen it boot into runlevel 3, you've probably "
"noticed the cute ANSI/ASCII-art Tux that precedes the login prompt. This "
"hint will tell you how to create the same effect on your LFS system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:44
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Notes\n"
"-----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:49
msgid ""
"In an attempt to make this easier to read, all \"code blocks\" that you "
"should execute on the commandline start and end with \"##--CODE--##\". Feel "
"free to copy that onto the commandline along with the code itself, it won't "
"hurt anything."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:51
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Requirements\n"
"------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:54
msgid "All you need is the source code to linux logo, which can be found here:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:56
msgid "http://www.deater.net/weave/vmwprod/linux_logo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:58
msgid ""
"I used version 4.06 to write this hint, but other versions will work as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:61
msgid ""
"This hint uses SysVInit bootscripts, though it's not hard at all to "
"implement this with BSD-style bootscripts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Instructions\n"
"------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:66
msgid "Unpack linux_logo, and compile it like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:71
msgid "##--CODE--## make logos-all && make install ##--CODE--##"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:74
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"2. I advise you to read the README and configure linuxlogo to the way you "
"want\n"
"it to display the logo when you are logging in. I configured mine like "
"this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:79
msgid ""
"##--CODE--## echo -n '-L 13 -F \"\\n\\nFeztux GNU/#O #V on #H.\\nCompiled "
"#C.' > /etc/linux_logo.conf echo '\\n#N #M #X #T #P.\\n#R RAM, #B Bogomips "
"Total. \\n#E\"' >> /etc/linux_logo.conf ##--CODE--##"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:82
msgid ""
"Explanation: we are creating the config file for the program, which really "
"is just a file that contains commandline options for it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:87
msgid ""
"The -L option tells it to use the 13th logo, which is the one I happen to "
"like the most, but keep in mind that you might be compiling with a different "
"set of logos, so your numbers may vary. (try \"linux_logo -L list\" to see a "
"list of available logos, and then pick the one you want)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:90
msgid ""
"The -F option configures how the system information is formatted (read the "
"readme on how to set this option)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:96
msgid ""
"If you want to have linux_logo clear the screen before printing the logo, "
"and thus hiding the output of your bootscripts after everything finishes "
"loading, add the -f option to this file. This also has the added benefit of "
"clearing the screen whenever you log out; so if other people use your "
"computer, they won't be able to see what you were doing before you logged "
"out."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:98
msgid "Now we'll make the bootscript for it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:103
msgid ""
"##--CODE--## cat > /etc/rc.d/init.d/issue << \"EOF\" #!/bin/bash # Begin "
"$rc_base/init.d/issue"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:106
msgid "source /etc/sysconfig/rc source $rc_functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:113
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case \"$1\" in\n"
"\tstart|stop)\n"
"\t\techo \"Setting /etc/issue...\"\n"
"\t\tlinux_logo -t \"Console: \\l\" >/etc/issue 2>&1\n"
"    evaluate_retval\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:119
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t*)\n"
"\t\techo \"Usage: $0 {start|stop}\"\n"
"\t\texit 1\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
"esac\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:124
msgid ""
"# End $rc_base/init.d/issue EOF chmod 755 /etc/rc.d/init.d/issue "
"##--CODE--##"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:130
msgid ""
"The -t option here simply specifies some custom text that we want to display "
"in the issue file, but that we wouldn't want to display when linux_logo is "
"run normally (which is why we don't put it in the config file). When you "
"boot, certain codes in the /etc/issue file are interpreted and replaced with "
"some information.  In this case, the '\\l' is being replaced with your "
"current tty."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:135
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"5. Finally, make the symlinks to the script. You can run the script while "
"your\n"
"computer boots and shuts down if you wish, but it really only makes sense "
"to\n"
"run it while the computer is booting. So, only make the symlink in "
"/etc/rc3.d,\n"
"assuming you boot to runlevel 3:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:140
msgid ""
"##--CODE--## cd /etc/rc.d/rc3.d && ln -s ../init.d/issue S35issue "
"##--CODE--##"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/linuxlogo.txt:142
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The End\n"
"-------\n"
msgstr ""

